    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1101_2022_10_31_514564__task_005/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To quantify these preferences with cooltools saddle (Fig 4), the approach is to: (i) group bins with similar properties into classes, (ii) average over all map pixels specified by the bins in each pair of classes (i.e. for each pair of classes p, q, summarize the collection of pixels {A ij | i in p, j in q})... cooltools operates on observed-over-expected contact frequencies, either based on raw counts or balanced data, and can be restricted to either cis or trans portions of the genome wide map.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes saddle output as pairwise class-averaged contact frequency matrices (typically visualized as 2D heatmaps), but does not explicitly specify NPZ file format as the output format. The paper states outputs are pandas DataFrames or NumPy arrays: 'Return widely-used Python data structures, pandas dataframes, and numpy arrays, for user-facing outputs' (passage 5). NPZ is a NumPy format, but the paper does not explicitly name NPZ as the output format for saddle.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_005",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "NPZ file containing untransformed saddle data matrix indexed by digitized compartment bins",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T17:58:11.619485+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1101_2022_10_31_514564__task_005/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Pairwise summaries, obtained by averaging over pairs of regions assigned to a set of classes, are a straightforward way to quantify these preferences... Pairwise summaries have also been used to quantify GC content and fragment length biases [32]. To quantify these preferences with cooltools saddle (Fig 4), the approach is to: (i) group bins with similar properties into classes, (ii) average over all map pixels specified by the bins in each pair of classes",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes saddle output as pairwise class-averaged contact frequency matrices (2D heatmaps), not as a scalar 'saddle strength' metric. The paper does not mention a scalar output quantifying compartment interaction asymmetry from the saddle function. The saddle plot itself is a 2D visualization, not a single scalar value.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_005",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Saddle strength scalar (float) quantifying compartment interaction asymmetry",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T17:58:11.619485+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1101_2022_10_31_514564__task_005/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The candidate card focuses on input/output specifications for cooltools.saddle and cooltools.digitize, which are described in the paper. However, the expected outputs claim about 'saddle strength scalar' does not align with the paper's description of saddle output as 2D matrices/heatmaps.",
        "The paper does not explicitly discuss cooltools.digitize as a separate function; digitization is described as part of the compartment analysis workflow (binning eigenvector values into classes), but the paper does not name a specific 'digitize' function."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 2,
