    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/cis-contact-frequency-analysis/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The shape of P(s) reflects folding patterns at different length scales, from those of adjacent nucleosomes to full chromosomes [26,27], and can be quantified with its derivative. P(s) varies through the cell cycle, across cell types, and is modified by structural maintenance of chromosomes complexes (SMCs) in interphase, mitosis, and meiosis.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes P(s) as a foundational analysis that characterizes chromatin organization at multiple scales.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "cis-contact-frequency-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have loaded a cooler file containing Hi-C contact matrices and need to quantify how contact probability decays with genomic distance within a single chromosome. This is typically one of the first analyses performed on Hi-C data to characterize the global organizational p",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:01:19.471901+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/compartment-strength-quantification/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Pairwise summaries, obtained by averaging over pairs of regions assigned to a set of classes, are a straightforward way to quantify these preferences... For genome folding, these are most frequently used to quantify the strength of compartmentalization after assigning classes from the extracted compartment profile. The pattern of preferences revealed by this averaging (where contacts are disfavored between active and inactive chromatin) led to these summaries being referred to as 'saddle plots'",
      "asbval:note": "Passage describes saddle plots as quantifying compartmentalization strength via pairwise class averaging, which aligns with the card's description of saddle strength as a metric derived from 2D saddle matrices.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "compartment-strength-quantification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Quantify the asymmetry of A/B compartment interactions in Hi-C contact matrices by computing saddle strength\u2014a scalar metric derived from a 2D saddle matrix aggregating contact frequency by digitized eigenvector compartment pairs.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:01:31.475500+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/compartment-strength-quantification/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A second prominent signal in mammalian interphase contact maps is plaid patterns that appear both within and between chromosomes, termed chromosome compartments. These plaid patterns reflect tendencies of chromosome regions to make more frequent contacts with regions of the same type: active regions have increased contact frequency with other active regions, and inactive regions tend to contact other inactive regions more frequently.",
      "asbval:note": "Passage describes A/B compartmentalization as the spatial segregation of active and inactive regions, which is the biological phenomenon the card's metric quantifies.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "compartment-strength-quantification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This metric summarizes the degree to which the genome is partitioned into spatially segregated A and B compartments.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:01:31.475500+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/compartment-strength-quantification/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "[SUBSTRING-MATCH for cooltools | role: Core library providing digitize() and saddle() functions]",
      "asbval:note": "Paper introduces cooltools as a suite of computational tools for Hi-C analysis. Passages [6] and [7] explicitly describe cooltools saddle module for computing saddle plots and pairwise class averaging.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "compartment-strength-quantification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "cooltools",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:01:31.475500+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/compartment-strength-quantification/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To quantify these preferences with cooltools saddle (Fig 4), the approach is to: (i) group bins with similar properties into classes, (ii) average over all map pixels specified by the bins in each pair of classes (i.e. for each pair of classes p, q, summarize the collection of pixels {A ij | i in p, j in q}). Bins can be assigned to classes either by discrete properties, or by discretizing a quantitative signal.",
      "asbval:note": "Passage describes the cooltools saddle function performing binning (discretization) and pairwise averaging, matching the card's description of digitize() and saddle() functions.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "compartment-strength-quantification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[0].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Core library providing digitize() and saddle() functions for binning eigenvector tracks and computing saddle matrices and strength metrics",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:01:31.475500+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
