    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/tsv-file-io-and-formatting/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "cooltools returns P(s) curves smoothed in log-space using a numba-accelerated approach... To quantify P(s) at sub-kilobase resolution (Fig 2), cooltools avoids conversion from sparse-to-dense matrices. Instead, the calculation is done by iterating over chunks of pixels stored in coolers, assigning pixels to regions, and aggregating at each distance.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms cooltools performs log-space smoothing of P(s) and returns smoothed curves, but the workflow described operates directly on cooler HDF5 files, not on pre-loaded TSV tables. The paper does not describe a TSV\u2192logbin_expected\u2192TSV pipeline.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "tsv-file-io-and-formatting",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "cooltools applies logbin_expected smoothing function to loaded TSV expected table and generates output TSV with binned and smoothed P(s)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:06:06.308998+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/tsv-file-io-and-formatting/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "Black is not mentioned anywhere in the paper passages. No evidence of black being used in cooltools development.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "tsv-file-io-and-formatting",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "black code formatter used during development to ensure consistent and readable style in file I/O code",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:06:06.308998+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/tsv-file-io-and-formatting/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Cooltools provides a paired command line interface (CLI) and Python application programming interface (API)... The user-facing API and CLI both have a standard format for arguments and take a cooler as their first input. For other types of genomic data besides Hi-C, the cooltools API accepts pandas dataframes... Leverage the Python data science stack to promote interoperability. Cooltools delegates to numpy, scipy, and pandas when possible... Return widely-used Python data structures, pandas dataframes, and numpy arrays, for user-facing outputs.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms cooltools is a Python package that uses pandas for data handling and I/O.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "tsv-file-io-and-formatting",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Python as primary language for reading, validating, and writing TSV files using built-in I/O or pandas",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:06:06.308998+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/tsv-file-io-and-formatting/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The contact frequency decreases rapidly with genomic separation within chromosomes... This feature is interchangeably referred to as the: (i) expected because locus-specific features increase or decrease contact frequency relative to this major trend, (ii) scaling which is borrowed from the polymer physics literature, (iii) P(s), or contact probability, P, as a function of genomic separation, s.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper discusses expected contact frequency and P(s) calculation but does not describe a workflow where precomputed TSV tables with specific columns (dist_bp, contact_frequency, n_valid) are loaded and smoothed. The paper describes computing P(s) directly from cooler files.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "tsv-file-io-and-formatting",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When to use: You have computed or received a precomputed expected contact frequency table with columns such as dist_bp, contact_frequency, and n_valid, and need to persist it in a human-readable, column-labeled format suitable for downstream smoothing operations like logbin_expec",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:06:06.308998+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/tsv-file-io-and-formatting/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Cooltools works with processed Hi-C data and is not concerned with mapping workflows... Cooltools is built directly on top of the cooler storage format and library, which allows it to operate on sparse matrices and/or out-of-core, either on raw counts or normalized contact matrices.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms cooltools works with cooler format directly for raw/processed contact data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1371-journal-pcbi-1012067",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "tsv-file-io-and-formatting",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When NOT to use: Raw Hi-C contact matrix is still in cooler HDF5 format and has not yet been aggregated into expected frequency profile \u2014 use cooler's native API instead",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:06:06.308998+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
